Here's a simple C++ function that uses the Pugixml library to convert markdown text to HTML. First, you need to install the Pugixml library. You can do this by running the following command in your terminal:

```bash
sudo apt-get install libpugixml-dev
```

Then, you can use the following code:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <pugixml.hpp>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdownText) {
    pugi::xml_document doc;
    pugi::xml_parse_result result = doc.load_string(markdownText.c_str());

    if (!result) {
        return "";
    }

    pugi::xml_node root = doc.document_element();
    std::string htmlText = root.print();

    return htmlText;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Heading\n## Subheading\nThis is a paragraph.";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHtml(markdownText);
    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This function loads the markdown text into a pugi::xml_document, parses it, and then prints the resulting HTML. The `print()` function is used to convert the parsed XML document to a string.

Please note that this is a basic example and does not handle all possible markdown syntax. For a more comprehensive solution, you may want to use a dedicated markdown to HTML converter library.

